      "rationale": "Three-level GCI study completed; GCI below 3.5% for velocity and wall shear stress quantities. Discretization error is included in the Monte Carlo UQ input distributions. However, temporal discretization error for transient impeller passage effects was not separately quantified and is subsumed under a conservative estimate."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented with uncertainty bounds and must span the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental data provides flow rate, pressure rise, and hemolysis index at 5 operating points. Test condition uncertainties are documented in the FDA dataset publication. Two of five operating points fall at the boundary of the COU envelope; interpolation uncertainty at these boundary conditions is acknowledged but not fully quantified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative metric (e.g., E%, MAPE, or validation uncertainty interval) must be reported comparing predicted and experimental hemolysis index values.",
      "rationale": "Mean absolute percentage error of 18.4% across 5 operating points. Prediction intervals from Monte Carlo UQ bracket experimental measurements at 4 of 5 points (80% coverage). The single outlier at high-flow low-speed condition exceeds the 95% prediction interval, indicating a potential model form deficiency at off-design conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (hemolysis index) must be the same metric used in the regulatory submission decision.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) is used consistently as the QoI in both the validation dataset and the regulatory decision criterion. Minor differences in the hemolysis model formulation (Giersiepen vs. Zhang power-law coefficients) introduce a systematic offset that is partially corrected by a calibration factor applied uniformly across operating points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must be conducted on the same device geometry and at operating conditions representative of the intended COU, or a formal extrapolation argument must be provided.",
      "rationale": "Validation is performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump, which is a simplified research geometry, not the actual VAD device geometry. A geometric similarity argument is provided but the actual device has a more complex impeller profile and smaller blade gaps. The extrapolation from generic pump to clinical VAD is the primary credibility gap at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated to a level that does not materially affect the QoI; round-off and algorithmic errors must be characterized.",
      "rationale": "Iterative residuals converge six orders of magnitude for steady-state runs. Rotating reference frame periodicity residuals are monitored but convergence criterion for impeller-volute interface is less stringent (four orders of magnitude) due to solver limitations. Round-off error is not separately characterized."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Procedures must be in place to detect and prevent analyst errors in model setup, boundary condition specification, and post-processing of hemolysis results.",
      "rationale": "No formal use-error assessment was conducted. Simulation setup was reviewed by a single analyst; independent peer review of boundary condition inputs and post-processing scripts was not performed. This factor is flagged as an epistemic gap at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The turbulence model and hemolysis damage accumulation model must be justified for the flow regime and geometry of the VAD COU, with comparison to higher-fidelity references where available.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on prior literature for pump flows. No LES or DNS reference data available for the specific operating regime. Hemolysis power-law model is acknowledged to be empirically derived from in-vitro data under idealized shear conditions; applicability to complex three-dimensional rotating flow paths is a recognized model form uncertainty that is not bounded by available validation data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All uncertain model inputs must be characterized with probability distributions and propagated through the model via Monte Carlo or equivalent UQ method. A screening sensitivity study must identify which inputs drive output variance.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo UQ (N=2000) was performed propagating uncertainty in inlet flow rate (±5%), rotational speed (±2%), blood viscosity (±15%), and hemolysis model coefficients (±20%). A screening sensitivity study using Pearson correlation coefficients was conducted during the UQ analysis setup phase and is described in the UQ narrative report, identifying hemolysis model coefficient C as the dominant variance contributor. However, the structured sensitivity analysis results are not formally encoded as a linked artifact in this credibility package; the dominant input drivers therefore remain uncharacterized in the machine-readable evidence record. Input distributions were assigned based on literature ranges rather than device-specific measurements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental samples used for validation must be characterized for material properties and manufacturing variability representative of the clinical device population.",
      "rationale": "The FDA benchmark uses a single 3D-printed pump geometry; manufacturing variability across device population is not characterized. No information on blood analog fluid lot-to-lot variability is available in the dataset. Flagged as epistemic gap."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Boundary conditions and material properties in the simulation must be demonstrated to match the experimental test conditions within acceptable tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Nominal boundary conditions from the FDA dataset are applied directly. Uncertainty in the experimental flow rate measurement (±3%) and pressure measurement (±2%) are incorporated into UQ input distributions, but formal equivalency demonstration comparing simulation inputs to experimental conditions on a point-by-point basis was not performed. Flagged as epistemic gap at MRL 5."
    }
